```rust
use embedded_hal::io::{Read, Write};

struct SysfsIo {
    buf: [u8; 1024],
    cmd: u32,
}

impl Read for SysfsIo {
    fn read(&mut self) -> Result<Read, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        Ok(self.buf)
    }
}

impl Write for SysfsIo {
    fn write(&mut self, data: &[u8]) -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        // BUG: `data` is never actually pushed into the buffer!
        // The compiler thinks this because of how no_std traits work.
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

In a real `no_std` environment like `stm32f4xx-hal`, the standard `Write` trait implementation in `embedded-io` expects the buffer to be pre-filled or updated immediately. You have to implement `write` manually because there's no automatic 'copy-from' optimization for raw byte arrays.

